{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016a9BsKb4qMB1fdQjHgbswS","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Project Settings File: config.toml\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-06\n     4→**Status:** Design\n     5→\n     6→## Problem\n     7→\n     8→The per-project settings file is `.cloche/config` with no extension, making it\n     9→ambiguous and inconsistent with the TOML library in use.\n    10→\n    11→## Change\n    12→\n    13→Rename to `.cloche/config.toml`. No backwards compatibility with the old filename.\n    14→\n    15→## Default file (created by `cloche init`)\n    16→\n    17→```toml\n    18→# Cloche project configuration\n    19→\n    20→[orchestration]\n    21→concurrency        = 1\n    22→stagger_seconds    = 1.0\n    23→# list_tasks_command = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    24→# dedup_seconds    = 300\n    25→\n    26→[evolution]\n    27→enabled           = true\n    28→debounce_seconds  = 30\n    29→min_confidence    = \"medium\"\n    30→max_prompt_bullets = 50\n    31→```\n    32→\n    33→Notes:\n    34→- `orchestration.concurrency` defaults to `1` (single run at a time).\n    35→- `orchestration.stagger_seconds` adds delay between consecutive launches (default `1.0`).\n    36→- `orchestration.list_tasks_command` (optional) is a shell command that outputs a JSON array of\n    37→  task objects (`[{\"id\":\"...\",\"title\":\"...\",\"description\":\"...\"}]`). When set, the daemon\n    38→  picks tasks and passes the ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var.\n    39→- `orchestration.dedup_seconds` (default `300`) prevents reassignment of the same task ID\n    40→  within the timeout window.\n    41→- Commented-out keys show optional overrides that rarely need changing.\n    42→\n    43→## Code changes\n    44→\n    45→| File | Change |\n    46→|------|--------|\n    47→| `internal/config/config.go` | `Load()`: change path from `\"config\"` to `\"config.toml\"` |\n    48→| `cmd/cloche/init.go` | Add `config.toml` to the files created by init |\n    49→| `.cloche/config` (existing file in this repo) | Rename to `.cloche/config.toml` |\n    50→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d71b425a-1bee-4cc0-883d-648d8272f0ee","uuid":"20f4c195-8d9d-4895-adde-89a51ff5ab46","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-06-config-toml-design.md","content":"# Project Settings File: config.toml\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-06\n**Status:** Design\n\n## Problem\n\nThe per-project settings file is `.cloche/config` with no extension, making it\nambiguous and inconsistent with the TOML library in use.\n\n## Change\n\nRename to `.cloche/config.toml`. No backwards compatibility with the old filename.\n\n## Default file (created by `cloche init`)\n\n```toml\n# Cloche project configuration\n\n[orchestration]\nconcurrency        = 1\nstagger_seconds    = 1.0\n# list_tasks_command = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n# dedup_seconds    = 300\n\n[evolution]\nenabled           = true\ndebounce_seconds  = 30\nmin_confidence    = \"medium\"\nmax_prompt_bullets = 50\n```\n\nNotes:\n- `orchestration.concurrency` defaults to `1` (single run at a time).\n- `orchestration.stagger_seconds` adds delay between consecutive launches (default `1.0`).\n- `orchestration.list_tasks_command` (optional) is a shell command that outputs a JSON array of\n  task objects (`[{\"id\":\"...\",\"title\":\"...\",\"description\":\"...\"}]`). When set, the daemon\n  picks tasks and passes the ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var.\n- `orchestration.dedup_seconds` (default `300`) prevents reassignment of the same task ID\n  within the timeout window.\n- Commented-out keys show optional overrides that rarely need changing.\n\n## Code changes\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `internal/config/config.go` | `Load()`: change path from `\"config\"` to `\"config.toml\"` |\n| `cmd/cloche/init.go` | Add `config.toml` to the files created by init |\n| `.cloche/config` (existing file in this repo) | Rename to `.cloche/config.toml` |\n","numLines":50,"startLine":1,"totalLines":50}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01PfcPY4p6bihJvDnDNTbMV2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MDGbUh6KMkrznYCfhfAML4","name":"Grep","input":{"pattern":"stop_on_error|orchestration|cloche\\.toml|max_consecutive","output_mode":"content","path":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","-n":true,"context":3},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":683,"cache_read_input_tokens":20607,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":683},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d71b425a-1bee-4cc0-883d-648d8272f0ee","uuid":"1023cd84-a622-465b-bfe0-0892220e0c1f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MDGbUh6KMkrznYCfhfAML4","type":"tool_result","content":"270-fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n271-\n272-A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to three\n273:host workflow phases for orchestration:\n274-\n275-| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n276-|-------|--------------|---------|\n--\n279-| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n280-\n281-Additionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\n282:automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n283-web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. A task is\n284-considered stale when it has `in_progress` status but no active worker is running for\n285-it (e.g. after a failed run or daemon restart). The workflow receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`.\n--\n380-\n381-## Setting Up Host Workflows\n382-\n383:Host workflows are the orchestration layer that ties everything together. When you\n384-run `cloche init`, a minimal host workflow with just a `main` workflow is generated.\n385-As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows to automate\n386-task discovery and cleanup.\n--\n403-The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n404-tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n405-\n406:**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n407-loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n408-\n409-**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n--\n550-\n551-The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n552-\n553:1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n554-2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n555-3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n556-4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n--\n700-\n701-Without a run ID, shows a daemon status overview: version, run statistics (past hour),\n702-and active runs. In a project directory, also shows project name, concurrency, and\n703:orchestration loop state. Use `--all` to show global stats instead of project-specific\n704-stats.\n705-\n706-| Flag | Description |\n--\n829-|------|---------|-------------|\n830-| `--name <label>` | _(cwd lookup)_ | Look up project by label (e.g. `cloche`) instead of directory. |\n831-\n832:Output includes: config settings (active, concurrency, stagger, dedup, stop_on_error,\n833-evolution), orchestrator loop state (running/stopped/halted), currently active runs,\n834-and known container and host workflow names. When the loop is halted due to\n835:`stop_on_error`, the halt error message is displayed.\n836-\n837-### `cloche get`\n838-\n--\n861-cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n862-```\n863-\n864:Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n865-upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n866-state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n867-\n--\n871-\n872-### `cloche loop`\n873-\n874:Start, stop, or resume the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n875-tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n876-\n877-```\n--\n886-\n887-`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n888-\n889:`cloche loop resume` clears the halted state after a `stop_on_error` halt, allowing\n890:the loop to resume picking up new work. See `stop_on_error` in the project config.\n891-\n892-### `cloche --version`\n893-\n--\n923-my-project/\n924-├── .cloche/\n925-│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n926:│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflows (contain host { } blocks)\n927-│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n928-│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration\n929-│   ├── prompts/              # Prompt templates"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d71b425a-1bee-4cc0-883d-648d8272f0ee","uuid":"7a278d6d-f77f-4cb4-9e79-caee72e8a587","tool_use_result":{"mode":"content","numFiles":0,"filenames":[],"content":"270-fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n271-\n272-A single file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon uses up to three\n273:host workflow phases for orchestration:\n274-\n275-| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n276-|-------|--------------|---------|\n--\n279-| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n280-\n281-Additionally, a **`release-task`** host workflow may be defined. This is not part of the\n282:automatic orchestration loop — it is invoked on demand (e.g. from the\n283-web dashboard) to release a stale claimed task back to `open` status. A task is\n284-considered stale when it has `in_progress` status but no active worker is running for\n285-it (e.g. after a failed run or daemon restart). The workflow receives `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`.\n--\n380-\n381-## Setting Up Host Workflows\n382-\n383:Host workflows are the orchestration layer that ties everything together. When you\n384-run `cloche init`, a minimal host workflow with just a `main` workflow is generated.\n385-As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows to automate\n386-task discovery and cleanup.\n--\n403-The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n404-tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n405-\n406:**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n407-loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n408-\n409-**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n--\n550-\n551-The three-phase model enables fully automate